Let's do a deep analysis of Overloading in Java. Overloading is one of the most important OOP concepts.

1. What is Method Overloading?

Method Overloading means:

Having multiple methods with the same name but different parameters in the same class.

The compiler decides which method to call based on the method signature.

Method Signature contains:
Method name
Number of parameters
Type of parameters
Order of parameters

Return type is NOT part of method signature.

Example:

class Calculator {

    void add(int a, int b) {
        System.out.println(a + b);
    }

    void add(double a, double b) {
        System.out.println(a + b);
    }

    void add(int a, int b, int c) {
        System.out.println(a + b + c);
    }
}

Here add() is overloaded 3 times.

2. Why do we use Overloading?

Suppose we don't have overloading:

addTwoNumbers()
addThreeNumbers()
addDoubleNumbers()

Many different names.

With overloading:

add()
add()
add()

Same operation, different inputs.

It improves:

readability
maintainability
compile-time polymorphism
3. Rules for Method Overloading
Rule 1: Parameters must change

Allowed:

Different number of parameters
void show(int a)

void show(int a, int b)

✔ Valid

Different type of parameters
void show(int a)

void show(String a)

✔ Valid

Different order of parameters
void show(int a, String b)

void show(String b, int a)

✔ Valid

4. What is NOT allowed?
Only changing return type

Wrong:

int add(int a,int b)
{
 return a+b;
}


double add(int a,int b)
{
 return a+b;
}

Compiler error.

Because:

method signature same

Return type doesn't matter.

Only changing access modifier

Wrong:

public void show(int a)

private void show(int a)

Not allowed.

Only changing static keyword

Wrong:

static void show(int a)

void show(int a)

Not allowed.

5. Access Modifiers in Overloading

Any access modifier is allowed:

class Test {


public void display(int a)
{

}


private void display(String s)
{

}


protected void display(double d)
{

}


void display(boolean b)
{

}

}

All valid.

Because parameters are different.

6. Can static methods be overloaded?

YES.

Example:

class Demo {


static void show(int a)
{
System.out.println(a);
}


static void show(String s)
{
System.out.println(s);
}

}

Call:

Demo.show(10);
Demo.show("Hello");

Works.

7. Can constructor be overloaded?

YES.

Very common.

Example:

class Student {


Student()
{
System.out.println("Default");
}


Student(String name)
{
System.out.println(name);
}


Student(String name,int age)
{
System.out.println(name+" "+age);
}

}

Creating objects:

Student s1 = new Student();

Student s2 = new Student("Akash");

Student s3 = new Student("Akash",22);
8. Constructor Overloading Rules

Same rules apply.

Allowed:

Student(int id)

Student(String name)

Allowed.

Not allowed:

Student(int id)

public Student(int id)

No.

Because same parameter list.

9. Can main() be overloaded?

YES.

Example:

class Test {


public static void main(String[] args)
{
System.out.println("normal");
}


public static void main(int a)
{
System.out.println(a);
}


}

Allowed.

But JVM only calls:

main(String[] args)
10. Same type or different type parameters?

Both allowed.

Same type
void add(int a,int b)

void add(int a,int b,int c)

same type, different count.

✔

Different type
void add(int a,int b)

void add(double a,double b)

✔

Mixed type
void show(int a,String b)

void show(String a,int b)

✔

11. Overloading with Inheritance

Example:

class Parent {

void show(int a)
{
}

}


class Child extends Parent {


void show(String s)
{

}

}

Child has overloaded method.

12. Varargs and Overloading

Example:

void display(int... a)
{

}


void display(int a,int b)
{

}

Allowed.

But:

void display(int... a)

void display(int[] a)

Not allowed.

Because varargs internally becomes array.

13. Ambiguous Overloading

Important case:

class Demo{


void show(int a)
{
}


void show(float a)
{
}


public static void main(String args[])
{

Demo d=new Demo();

d.show(10);

}

}

Which runs?

int version

because exact match.

Another:

void show(Integer a)

void show(String a)


show(null);

Compiler error.

Why?

Both can accept null.

14. Overloading vs Overriding
Overloading	Overriding
Same class	Parent-child
Same name	Same name
Different parameters	Same parameters
Compile time	Runtime
Return type can differ	Return type same/covariant
15. Real Example

ArrayList:

list.add(10);

list.add("hello");

list.add(0,"Akash");

add() is overloaded.

Different parameters.

Final Summary

For overloading:

✅ Same method name
✅ Same class
✅ Different parameters
✅ Any access modifier allowed
✅ static allowed
✅ constructor allowed
✅ return type can change but not alone
✅ final method can overload
❌ Only changing return type not allowed
❌ Only changing access modifier not allowed
❌ Only changing static not allowed

This is compile-time polymorphism.